    <!-- WHY ADULTS SPECIFICALLY -->
    <h2 id="why-adults">Why Melatonin Gummies for Adults Are a Different Conversation</h2>

    <p>Most melatonin marketing speaks to "people who can't sleep" as a single audience, but the right melatonin strategy is meaningfully different for adults than for children, and different again for adults over 65. Three biological factors explain why the adult conversation deserves its own guide: endogenous melatonin production peaks in adolescence and declines steadily through adulthood, the cytochrome P450 enzymes that metabolize melatonin shift in efficiency with age, and the polypharmacy common in adult life introduces drug interaction concerns that simply do not exist in the pediatric or younger adult population.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">478%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">Maximum variation from labeled melatonin dose found in a <strong>2017 Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine study</strong>. Fewer than 30% of melatonin supplements fell within 10% of their stated dose. For adults using melatonin nightly, third-party testing is essential — not optional.</p>
    </div>

    <p>For adult buyers, three decisions matter more than the brand: <strong>the right dose</strong> (almost always lower than what is on the shelf), <strong>the right release mechanism</strong> (immediate vs extended depending on your specific sleep problem), and <strong>the right verification</strong> (USP or NSF certification given the documented label inaccuracy in this category). Get those three right and the brand name becomes secondary.</p>

    <!-- DOSING CONVERSATION -->
    <h2 id="dose-for-adults">The Adult Melatonin Dose: Why Less Is Almost Always Better</h2>

    <p>The melatonin supplement market has a dosing problem. Products ranging from 1mg to 20mg are sold side by side in the same aisle, suggesting that more must be better. The clinical evidence says the opposite. Your body naturally produces approximately 0.1 to 0.3mg of melatonin per night. Supplemental doses of 0.5 to 3mg are sufficient to raise blood melatonin to the levels that effectively signal the circadian clock for sleep. Doses above 5mg provide diminishing returns — they do not improve sleep quality proportionally but do increase the risk of morning grogginess, vivid nightmares, and daytime sleepiness.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Dose accuracy matters most</strong>
        <p>With content variations up to 478% from label claims, choosing a brand with documented third-party testing (USP, NSF) ensures you actually receive the dose on the label — the foundation of effective sleep supplementation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lower doses often work better</strong>
        <p>The body's melatonin receptors can become desensitized at high doses. MIT research found 0.3mg optimal. Most sleep specialists recommend fewer than 5mg for initial use, increasing only if needed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Timing matters as much as dose</strong>
        <p>Melatonin signals circadian timing, not sedation. Take 30-60 minutes before target bedtime. Consistent timing every night reinforces the circadian cue more effectively than increasing the dose.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Release mechanism for sleep type</strong>
        <p>Immediate-release for sleep onset insomnia (difficulty falling asleep). Extended-release for sleep maintenance (waking in the night). Dual-release combines both for comprehensive support.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

