    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Melatonin Gummies for Adults</h2>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What is the right melatonin dose for adults?</summary>
      <p>Sleep researchers recommend starting at 0.5 to 1mg and increasing to a maximum of 3 to 5mg only if lower doses are insufficient. MIT research found 0.3mg sufficient to raise blood melatonin to natural nighttime levels. Higher doses (10mg+) provide diminishing returns and increase the risk of morning grogginess, vivid dreams, and headaches. Most adults do better at the lower end of this range than at high doses.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How accurate is the melatonin content in gummies?</summary>
      <p>A 2017 study found melatonin content varied by -83% to +478% from label claims. Fewer than 30% of products were within 10% of the stated dose. USP Verification, NSF Certification, or ConsumerLab approval is essential to ensure dose accuracy — without third-party testing, you may be getting anywhere from a fraction to several times the labeled amount.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Can melatonin interfere with adult medications?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Blood thinners, immunosuppressants, diabetes medications, seizure medications, and blood pressure medications can all interact with melatonin. SSRIs and sedatives can amplify melatonin's effects. Adults taking any prescription medication should consult their healthcare provider before starting nightly melatonin, particularly if over 50 when polypharmacy becomes more common.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Is melatonin safe to take every night?</summary>
      <p>Short-term nightly use up to 3 months is supported by clinical trial safety data. Long-term nightly use beyond 3 months has limited safety data. The American Academy of Sleep Medicine does not recommend indefinite nightly melatonin use without medical supervision. For occasional insomnia or jet lag, melatonin is well-suited. For chronic insomnia, address underlying causes with a sleep specialist rather than relying on indefinite supplementation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What is the difference between regular and extended-release melatonin?</summary>
      <p>Immediate-release melatonin raises blood levels within 20-40 minutes and is cleared within 4-5 hours — best for sleep onset insomnia. Extended-release melatonin sustains elevated levels over 6-8 hours — better for sleep maintenance issues such as waking at 3 AM. Some products use dual-release technology combining both for comprehensive sleep architecture support, particularly useful for adults over 50.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Does melatonin affect hormones or fertility in adults?</summary>
      <p>At standard supplementation doses (0.5 to 5mg), melatonin has not demonstrated clinically significant effects on reproductive hormones in short-term studies. As a hormone itself, long-term high-dose use warrants medical supervision. Adults trying to conceive should discuss melatonin use with their healthcare provider, and chronic use above 5mg daily should be medically supervised.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Do older adults need different melatonin doses?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Endogenous melatonin production declines with age — adults over 65 produce roughly half the nightly melatonin of younger adults, making supplementation more impactful. However, older adults are also more sensitive to side effects including grogginess and dizziness, which raises fall risk. Start at 0.5mg of an immediate-release formulation, taken 30-60 minutes before bed, and only increase if needed. Extended-release formulations may help older adults with sleep maintenance insomnia.</p>
    </details>

